<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD6C80F3EE6E489691F9C51" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3EE6E4896F0F9C30" blockId="2.[166,630,1017,1045]" box="[166,630,1017,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">
<heading id="D09E8188FFD6C80F3EE6E4896F0F9C30" box="[166,630,1017,1045]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD6C80F3EE6E4896F0F9C30" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[166,630,1017,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="proboscidalis">
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD6C80F3EE6E4896CD29C31" bold="true" box="[166,427,1017,1044]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">Hypena proboscidalis</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE349691F9C51" blockId="2.[166,1225,1082,1332]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3C33E3496FC99C70" box="[627,688,1082,1109]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1719,1741]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1233,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig.7–12. Eggs of Erebidae:Hermeniinae:7, 8 — Pechipogo strigilata; Hypeninae:9–11 — Hypena proboscidalis; Phytometrinae: 12 — Colobochyla salicalis. Scale bars: 7–11 — 10 µm; 12 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Egg pale yellow. As egg develops, it becomes taupe (n = 2). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF84B15FFD6C80F3FAEE3296FEF9C50" author="Doring, E." box="[494,662,1114,1141]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" refId="ref3049" refString="Doring, E. Zur Morphologie der Schmetterlingseier. - Berlin: Akademie-Verlag, 1955. - 154 S." type="book" year="1955">Döring (1955)</bibRefCitation>
height 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD6C80F3CAEE3296E309C51" box="[750,841,1114,1140]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD6C80F3D84E329691B9C51" box="[964,1122,1114,1141]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" unit="mm" value="0.49" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.48">0.48–0.5 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD6C80F3E9BE3096D959DEC" pageId="2" pageNumber="555" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE3096CD99D11" blockId="2.[166,1225,1082,1332]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surface. Micropylar area sharply expressed, represented by rosette and 1 row long, narrow and pointed cells (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3DF1E3E96E869C90" box="[945,1023,1178,1205]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1719,1741]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1233,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig.7–12. Eggs of Erebidae:Hermeniinae:7, 8 — Pechipogo strigilata; Hypeninae:9–11 — Hypena proboscidalis; Phytometrinae: 12 — Colobochyla salicalis. Scale bars: 7–11 — 10 µm; 12 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Rosette slightly elevated, with 11–12 petalled cells. There are 16–20 of the 35–40 broad longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of micropylar area. Transverse walls filiform, much less distinct than ridges (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD6C80F3EBCE3896C319D30" box="[252,328,1274,1301]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1719,1741]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-5@3.[174,1233,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig.7–12. Eggs of Erebidae:Hermeniinae:7, 8 — Pechipogo strigilata; Hypeninae:9–11 — Hypena proboscidalis; Phytometrinae: 12 — Colobochyla salicalis. Scale bars: 7–11 — 10 µm; 12 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453438/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Aeropyles weakly expressed at walls junctions. The entire surface of small, densely placed fibers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE2366C539D5A" blockId="2.[166,1225,1348,1407]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">S h a p e o f g n a w e d h o l e s i n e g g s. Caterpillars nibble out oval opening at lateral part of egg.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD6C80F3E9BE2FC6D959DEC" blockId="2.[166,1224,1423,1481]" pageId="2" pageNumber="555">O v i p o s i t i o n. Eggs laid in single-layer tight clusters where they pressed one to another.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
